  "prompt": "What would cause a comminuted fracture in the elbow?",
  "response": "A comminuted fracture in the elbow occurs when the bone breaks into three or more pieces. This type of fracture is usually caused by high-energy trauma or significant force applied to the elbow. Common causes include:\n\n1. **High-Impact Trauma**:  \n   - Falls from a significant height onto the elbow.  \n   - Direct blows to the elbow, such as in motor vehicle accidents or sports injuries.  \n\n2. **Sports Injuries**:  \n   - Contact sports like football, rugby, or hockey, where direct force or collisions can occur.  \n   - Sports that involve falls, such as gymnastics, skiing, or skateboarding.  \n\n3. **Motor Vehicle Accidents**:  \n   - The elbow can sustain a comminuted fracture from direct impact or from bracing against the dashboard or steering wheel during a collision.  \n\n4. **Workplace or Industrial Accidents**:  \n   - Heavy machinery accidents or falls in construction or other high-risk workplaces.  \n\n5. **Osteoporosis or Bone Weakening**:  \n   - In individuals with weakened bones due to osteoporosis or other conditions, even a mild trauma can cause a comminuted fracture.  \n\n6. **Violent Assaults**:  \n   - Direct strikes to the elbow with a heavy object.  \n\nThe severity of a comminuted fracture often requires surgical intervention to realign and stabilize the bone fragments for proper healing. If you suspect an elbow fracture, seek immediate medical attention.",
